ChatGPT Poetry: Trump vs. Biden
text:
"Donald Trump, a name so bold, A man of fame, both young and old. With hair so bright and skin so tan, He's a businessman, a leader, a man.

With words so sharp, he captured our hearts, Making promises, playing his part. "Make America great again," he'd say, And people followed him all the way.

He tweeted and raged, never held back, No matter what, he'd always attack. He faced his foes, and took the stage, Defending his nation, with courage and rage.

But time passed by, and the story changed, His presidency came to an end, rearranged. Now, he's just a name, in history's pages, A man of the past, in America's ages.

Yet, he'll be remembered, for good or for ill, For his deeds and his words, always will. Donald Trump, a name so bold, A man of fame, both young and old."

---

"Joe Biden, a name so true, A man of grace, a heart that's kind and blue. With a smile so warm, and a voice so calm, He's a leader, a president, a man of qualm.

Born in Scranton, raised with pride, A son of Delaware, with a story to abide. With decades of service, he rose to the top, A vice president, then a leader, non-stop.

With a heart for the people, and a mind for the land, He took on the task, with a grip in his hand. Fighting for justice, for all to see, Leading the nation, with empathy.

Now, in the White House, he stands tall, Facing the challenges, and giving his all. For a better tomorrow, he fights with might, Bringing the country, back into the light.

Joe Biden, a name so true, A man of grace, a heart that's kind and blue. A leader, a president, a man we adore, A shining example, of what leadership is for."

Tell HN: Don't Be Afraid of Yandex
text:
There have been two threads in the last days about alternative search engines. I've noticed that whenever someone mentions Yandex, there is some skepticism and some users are "afraid" of using it due to being hosted in Russia.

Well let me tell you, there are some benefits to this: mainly it has a more permissive content policy compared to Google in some cases.

It's important to note that Yandex still complies with local laws and regulations, they are just different there.

I've used to resort to DDG when Google just wont (want to) display what I was looking for. It seems it has been neutered too. Yandex has not.

Ask HN: I just want to have fun programming again
text:
I've written in many very different languages in a professional full-time capacity in my many-year career. Now I'm interested in building something new and I have a clear idea in mind with some code already in C++ to proof-of-concept it for myself, but I'm struggling to find a direction forward that would be... fun. I don't mind challenging work, but I like an environment that feels sane and logical and where I am not facing loads of incidental complexity along the way. I'm also attracted to implementing my app cross-platform.

I just want to have some fun writing something without headaches, and that is seemingly less and less easy to achieve today. I'm not a fan of the complexity of either JavaScript or C++, and while I very much like Swift and working in the UIKit world, it's not so portable to platforms that many use.

I feel like there aren't really any good options in software development any more. It's always one big compromise with lots of possible decision fatigue. Every direction has drawbacks.

If I could write an app in a good static-compiled language that did not require extraneous expertise in CSS but that shipped on a web page and looked good using tools only in that language, with good interop with an HTML Canvas, that would be one possibility, but it is again a compromise -- no easy multithreading, dealing with all the front-end baggage to bundle or deploy such an app, etc.

Any recommendations? I'm not afraid of learning an entirely new language too.
